summary:
The Security Council adopted Resolution 2233 (2015) on 29 July 2015, recalling its previous resolutions on Iraq and reaffirming the country's independence, sovereignty, unity, and territorial integrity. The Council expressed grave concern at the security situation in Iraq due to the large-scale offensive by terrorist groups, particularly the Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), which has resulted in heavy civilian casualties, displacement of over three million Iraqis, and use of sexual violence. 

The Council emphasized the need for all Iraqis to work together to address the security and political challenges, and called on all political entities to overcome divisions and engage in an inclusive and timely political process. It underscored the importance of the international community supporting Iraq and encouraged the Government of Iraq to strengthen governance, promote human rights, and improve security. 

The Council also expressed concern for the humanitarian situation, with over three million internally displaced people, and urged all parties to provide adequate resources to address these issues. It emphasized the need for international and regional cooperation to support Iraq's fight against ISIL and prevent terrorist groups from using Iraqi and neighboring territories to carry out violence. 

The Council reiterated its commitment to Iraq's security and territorial integrity and expressed readiness to sanction individuals and entities supporting ISIL. It reaffirmed the importance of the United Nations Assistance Mission for Iraq (UNAMI) in advising, supporting, and assisting the Iraqi people and government to strengthen democratic institutions and advance inclusive political dialogue.
The Security Council,

Recalling its previous resolutions on Iraq, 

Condemns violent extremism and terrorism by ISIL, targeting women, girls, children, and vulnerable groups; 

Expresses grave concern over human rights abuses, including murder, kidnapping, enslavement, human trafficking, rape, and sexual slavery; 

Urges the Government of Iraq to promote and protect human rights, support the Independent High Commission for Human Rights, and ensure justice for terrorist acts; 

Encourages efforts to facilitate regional dialogue, resolve disputed internal boundaries, aid vulnerable groups, and promote protection of human rights; 

Reaffirms resolutions on women, peace, and security, and the importance of women's full participation; 

Welcomes commitments to relieve internally displaced persons, refugees, and returnees; 

Condemns destruction of cultural heritage, particularly by ISIL; 

Decides to:

1. Extend UNAMI's mandate until July 31, 2016; 

2. Continue UNAMI's mandate as stipulated in resolution 2169 (2014); 

3. Request the Secretary-General to report back on revising and prioritizing UNAMI's tasks within 90 days; 

4. Call upon the Government of Iraq to provide security and logistical support to UNAMI; 

5. Welcome contributions of Member States and call upon them to continue providing UNAMI with sufficient resources and support.
6. Expresses its intention to review the mandate of UNAMI in twelve months or sooner if requested by the Government of Iraq;

7. Requests the Secretary-General to report to the Council every three months on progress made towards the fulfilment of all UNAMIâ€™s responsibilities;

8. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
